{
  "texts": [
    "This suggests that for LLM-based unit test generation tasks, fine-tuning with smaller but higher-quality datasets is a more effective strategy than blindly pursuing data volume.",
    "For domain adaptation, datasets become even more granular, such as ⟨C++ code, unit test⟩ pairs in CPP-UT-Bench [17] or ⟨financial business rules, structured test elements⟩ pairs in LLM4Fin [149], all aiming to infuse project-or language-specific idioms into the model.",
    "The performance gains from fine-tuning on these specific tasks are substantial.",
    "In the large-scale study by [124], the best fine-tuned model for test generation (DeepSeek-Coder-6b) achieved a correct test rate of 33.68%, more than double the 16.21% of the SOTA method AthenaTest.",
    "For assertion generation, the impact is even more pronounced, with the fine-tuned model boosting the exact match score to 71.42%, in stark contrast to the 31.42% achieved by the previous SOTA method ATLAS [144].Fine-tuning can be further classified based on the scope and objectives of parameter adjustments:Full Fine-tuning (FFT)."
  ]
}